@startuml fig-ftp-indirect-transfer-sequence
skinparam backgroundColor white
skinparam defaultFontName Arial
skinparam defaultFontSize 11
skinparam shadowing false
skinparam sequenceMessageAlign center

title Indirect file transfer — client1 → server → client2

participant "client1\n(seminar9_client1)" as C1 #FFE0B2
participant "FTP server\n(seminar9_ftp_server)" as S #C8E6C9
participant "client2\n(seminar9_client2)" as C2 #BBDEFB

== Phase 1 — client1 uploads ==

C1 -> S : connect(ftp-server, 2121)
C1 -> S : LOGIN test / 12345
S --> C1 : 230 Login successful
C1 -> S : STOR from_client1.txt
S --> C1 : 226 Transfer complete

note right of S
  File is now stored in
  server-data/ volume.
end note

== Phase 2 — client2 downloads ==

C2 -> S : connect(ftp-server, 2121)
C2 -> S : LOGIN test / 12345
S --> C2 : 230 Login successful
C2 -> S : RETR from_client1.txt
S --> C2 : 226 Transfer complete

note right of C2
  File now resides in
  client2-data/ volume.
end note

legend bottom
  The two clients never communicate directly.
  The FTP server acts as a shared intermediary (store-and-forward).
  This pattern is common in organisational file-sharing scenarios.
endlegend
@enduml
